pr_review_comment_body:
TBH, I have pretty mixed feelings about assuming that the read will get everything in one shot.  It's perfectly valid to have short reads depending on the type of the underlying file descriptor (eg; sockets tend to return smaller chunks)

Can you add a helper function called something like `fread_all` that keeps going for short reads and use that in place of the `fread` calls in here?

The meat of that function would be something like:

```
total_len = 0;
while (true) {
   len = fread(..., to_read);
   if (len <= 0) {
      return 0; // Error before we read everything
   }  
   total_len += len;
   to_read -= len;
   buf += len;
   if (to_read == 0) {
     return total_len;
  }
} 
```

Hey, I just tested this on stage where I just landed a bug to remove the summary signatures for suites with only one test in them, and the results no longer look that good in that case:

![screen shot 2015-11-06 at 12 57 18 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/20569/11004402/0b8acdfa-8486-11e5-812c-e9c5c3bf4fa1.png)

I think we should remove the subtest details for that case. Something like this should do the trick:

````
detail['value'] = $scope.jobIds[series.signature][0].value;
detail['title'] = series.suite;
if (series.hasOwnProperty('test') && series.test.toLowerCase() !== series.suite) {
    detail['title'] += '_' + series.test.toLowerCase();
}
```

Note the change from suite -> title, which I believe is more accurate (you'll need to change the .html accordingly also, of course). I think with that change we should be good, sorry to make you have to do a bit more work. :)

I wouldn't create a separate class for that. Just enough to change `disabled` property in the parent class:
```python
@property
def disabled(self):
    return self.browser.get_attribute('disabled', self) == 'disabled' or 'disabled' in self.browser.classes(self)
```

This field will be present in the response even if no fields are ignored. As a specific example, if no variables are rejected, it will look like this:

```json
    "ignored_fields": {
        "extra_vars": {}
    },
```

It's these cases that the `in` logic will often miss. I realize that this might be very tricky for you to correctly check for.

We also can't _count_ on the fields being there, because it really won't be present in 2.4.5, which we still have to support. Let me know if you have any questions on these stipulations.

So, for what it's worth, Nova Scotia Power is lumping several of the fuels together under "Natural Gas" in their page https://www.nspower.ca/en/home/about-us/todayspower.aspx Curious which ones, I took a dive into the javascript backing that page: https://www.nspower.ca/site/renewables/assets/js/site.js?v=882528822

Lines 156-161:
```    
chartdata['repm'][repmCoal]['value'] = Math.round(mix['Solid Fuel']);
chartdata['repm'][repmNaturalGas]['value'] = Math.round(mix['CT\u0027s'] + mix['HFO/Natural Gas'] + mix['LM 6000\u0027s']);
chartdata['repm'][repmBiomass]['value'] = Math.round(mix['Biomass']);
chartdata['repm'][repmHydro]['value'] = Math.round(mix['Hydro']);
chartdata['repm'][repmWind]['value'] = Math.round(mix['Wind']);
chartdata['repm'][repmImports]['value'] = Math.round(mix['Imports']);
```

They're lumping CTs, HFO/Natural Gas, and LM 6000s together under the title "Natural Gas." Do we want to do the same or keep the granularity?

Looks like `State` should now be:

```
type State = {
  view: "line" | "bar" | "scatter" | "grid";
}
```

Yes, the literals, not the constants. Flow knows that the properties of `viewTypes` are not immutable properties.

Interface wise then I'd assume it would be like this:

```
import * as JSONTransfrom from '@nteract/transform-json';

// JSONTransform.component
// JSONTransform.MIMETYPE
```

Unless there's some better way to put static properties on React classes and declare those as a type. I suppose we _could_ extend `React.Component` even though people don't recommend it...

For readability.
In the template file , *config_items* and *libraries* are used directly instead of *require_config*
```
    require.config({
        paths: {
            {{ config_items | join(', ') }}
        }
    });
....
    require([{{ libraries | join(', ') }}], function(echarts) {
        {{ echarts_js_content_wrap(*charts) }}
    });
```
